    value: 노자(老子)《도덕경》에, “보아도 보이지 않는 것을 이(夷)라 칭하고, 듣자해도 들리지 않는 것은 희(希)라 칭하고, 덮치려 해도 덮칠 수 없는 것은 미(微)라 칭한다.” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D002] 오사(五祀) : '
    value: 《주례》 춘관대종백(春官大宗伯)에 “짐승의 피로써 사직(社稷)ㆍ오사(五祀)를 제사한다.” 하였고, 그 오사(五祀)에 대한 주석은 여러 가지가 있는데, 일 예를 들면 “청(靑)ㆍ적(赤)ㆍ황(黃)ㆍ백(白)ㆍ흑(黑)의 오색 제신(帝神)을 왕자(王者)의 궁중에 제사하는 것을 오사라 칭한다.” 하였음. 또 민가(民家)의 오사(五祀)가 있는데 즉 호신(戶神)ㆍ조신(竈神)ㆍ중류신(中霤神)ㆍ문신(門神)ㆍ정신(井神)에게 제사한다는 것임.
  - key: '[주-D003] 팔사(八蜡) : '
    value: 주(周) 때 해마다 농사를 마치고 12월에 선색(先嗇)ㆍ사색(司嗇)ㆍ농(農)ㆍ우표철(郵表畷)ㆍ묘호(貓虎)ㆍ방(坊)ㆍ수용(水庸)ㆍ곤충(昆蟲)의 여덟 신(神)에게 지내던 제사.
  - key: '[주-D004] 무격(巫覡) : '
    value: “여자 무당을 무(巫)라 칭하고 남자 무당을 격(覡)이라 칭한다.” 하였음. 《국어(國語)》의 초어(楚語)에 보임.
  - key: '[주-D005] 무우(舞雩) : '
    value: 우(雩)란 한신(旱神)에게 비를 비는 제사 이름임. 주례(周禮) 춘관사무(春官司巫)에, “만약 나라에 큰 가뭄이 들면 무당과 더불어 우단(雩壇)에 가서 춤을 추며 우제(雩祭)를 지낸다.” 하였음. 지금도 기우제(祈雨祭)를 무우제라 칭함.
  - key: '[주-D006] 도열(桃茢) : '
    value: 《예기》 단궁편(檀弓篇)에 “임금이 신하의 초상에 조문갈 적에는 무축(巫祝)ㆍ도열(桃茢)이 따른다.” 하였고, 그 주에, “도목(桃木)은 귀신이 두려워하는 것이요, 열(茢)은 담최(菼箒 갈대 모개로 만든 빗자루)인데, 상서롭지 못한 기운을 쓸어버리기 위한 것이다.” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D007] 상령(湘靈) : '
    value: 순(舜) 임금의 비(妃) 아황(娥皇)ㆍ여영(女英) 자매가 상수(湘水)에 빠져 죽어 상부인(湘夫人)이 되었기로 상평이라 한다. 《후한서》 마융전(馬融傳)에, “상령이 내리고 한녀(漢女)가 노닌다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 해약(海若) : '
    value: 해신(每神)의 이름임. 《장자》 추수편(秋水篇)에, “바다를 바라보고 약(若)을 향하여 탄식한다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 상류(湘纍) : '
    value: 죄없이 죽은 사람을 유(纍)라 칭함. 초(楚)나라 사람 굴원(屈原)이 상수(湘水)에 빠져 죽었기에 상류(湘纍)라 칭하였다. 《한서》 양웅전(揚雄傳)에, “삼가 초나라 상류에게 조문한다.”라는 구절이 있다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 후정화(後庭花) : '
    value: 옥수후정화(玉樹後庭花)의 약칭으로 음곡(音曲)의 이름임. 《수서(隋書)》 악지(樂志)에, “진 후주(陳後主) 숙보(叔寶)가 청악(淸樂) 중에 황려유(黃驪留)ㆍ옥수후정화(玉樹後庭花)ㆍ금차양빈수(金釵兩鬢垂) 등의 음곡을 창조해서 행신(幸臣)들과 더불어 가사(歌詞)를 지었는데 기염(綺艶)만을 숭상하여 극히 경박하였다. 남녀가 그 곡을 창화(唱和)하여 소리가 몹시 슬펐다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 참동계(參同契) : '
    value: 위백양(魏伯陽)이 저술한 책 이름인데, 참동계(參同契)라 칭한 것은 주역(周易)ㆍ황로(黃老)ㆍ노화(爐火) 등의 삼가(三家)를 참동하여 하나로 돌아와서 대도(大道)를 묘계(妙契)하였다는 것을 이름이다. 이 서(書)는 감리(坎離)ㆍ수화(水火)ㆍ용호(龍虎)ㆍ연홍(鉛汞)의 요결을 많이 말하며, 후세에 노화를 말하는 자의 시조(始祖)가 되었다.
  - key: '[주-D012] 적호(的呼) : '
    value: 속기(俗忌)에 있어 무릇 입관(入棺)이나 안장(安葬)할 때에 그날 일진(日辰)과 상충(相沖)되는 사람은 기피하게 되었는데, 이것을 적호일(的呼日)이라 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 眧 : '
    value: 昭
  - key: '[주-D002] 天 : '
    value: 夫
english:
  title: On Ghosts and Spirits
  author: Nam Hyooun
  language: eng
  text: "Someone asked Hyooun, \"Ghosts and spirits between heaven and earth are vague and dim, appearing to exist yet not existing, seeming solid yet hollow. Looking ahead they suddenly vanish behind; pointing here they are found there. Can you clarify this for me?\"\n\nI answered, \"The principle of ghosts and spirits is profound—what Confucius did not speak of, what Zilu never heard. Only the Chengs and Zhu Xi have barely touched upon it. How can one like myself, shallow in learning, presume to explain? Yet to know the future, one cannot avoid knowing the past; to understand life, one cannot escape understanding death. Seeking within the heart's chamber and examining it against all things, we may illuminate this principle.\n\nI have heard it said: ghost (gui) means to return, spirit (shen) means to extend. Thus all that gathers and extends within heaven and earth are spirits; all that scatters and returns are ghosts. From the greatest—the two principles, seven luminaries, twenty-eight mansions, twelve celestial branches—down to humans, animals, plants, wind, clouds, frost, dew, thunder and lightning, nothing is without the substance of ghosts and spirits. The one yin and one yang of the Book of Changes is their function.\n\nSpeaking of their substance: it is principle alone. Principle has no mind, no form. The Poetry says 'without sound or smell'; the Rites say 'unseen and unheard'; Laozi speaks of 'faint and dim'; Zhuangzi of 'seven sages confused.'\n\nSpeaking of their function: the great encompasses the beginning and end of the one primal force; the small encompasses morning and evening of a single day. The fixed positions of heaven, earth, water, and fire; the life and death of humans, animals, and plants; even those deep, dark, and difficult to comprehend matters—nothing escapes the realm of ghosts and spirits. Though one argued until white-haired and spoke with endless tongues, one could not exhaust it all.\n\nLet me speak of the great ones: The heavens contain brilliant vastness where sun, moon, and stars are suspended and the four seasons transform—these are the celestial spirits. The earth contains collected mass where the five peaks and four waters are sustained and flying, diving, moving, and growing things are nurtured—these are the earthly spirits. Those who obtained heaven and earth's balanced virtue, who shine together with sun and moon in waxing and waning, who accord with the four seasons in fortune and misfortune—these are human spirits.\n\nWhat sits fixed and unmoved, bearing plants and concealing myriad things, bringing forth prosperity for humankind—these are mountain spirits. What flows and moves, saturated everywhere, bringing forth shrimp and crabs, fish and dragons, carrying treasures flowing into the world—these are water spirits. What causes the five elements to generate and overcome one another, nourishing the five grains and sustaining human life—these are grain spirits. What brings forth flourishing and growth—these are the spirits of plants and trees. What governs one household—these are the spirits of the five sacrifices.\n\nIn their manifest aspect they are qi; in their subtle aspect they are principle. Speaking comprehensively, we call them ghosts and spirits.\n\nSomeone asked, 'If ghosts are such, can they have forms—appearing large or small, white or black—by which to distinguish them?'\n\nI said, 'No. That by which heaven is heaven and human beings are human beings is ghosts and spirits. From the beginning there is no physical form to distinguish. Large and small are the same ghost; black and white the same principle. When we sacrifice in the open with complete sincerity, the celestial spirits naturally respond. When we sacrifice in temples with complete sincerity, human ghosts naturally receive. With mountains, rivers, altars, and the five sacrifices, all is thus. Does not the Doctrine of the Mean say: sincerity cannot be concealed?'\n\nOne asked, 'Then do ghosts have form but possess qi?'\n\nI replied, 'In the bland emptiness there originally is not one thing. How could there be qi? It is principle alone. Yet when the sacrificer, through sincerity directed to that solitary knowing place, pours libations seeking in the silent darkness, then there appears that thing. This then becomes qi.'\n\nOne said, 'The Rites teach that only the Son of Heaven sacrifices to heaven and earth, only lords sacrifice to mountains and rivers, only descendants sacrifice to their ancestors. If you say that through sincerity one has substance, then if someone sacrificed to a ghost not his own, serving it with sincere heart, would that ghost also receive?'\n\nI answered, 'The spirit does not receive what is not according to ritual.'\n\n'How do you know the spirit will not receive what is not according to ritual?' he asked.\n\n'Because ghosts and spirits are principle. To sacrifice what does not accord with their principle means there is no principle by which they could receive. Therefore Mount Tai did not accept the ritual of the Ji clan, yet the Duke of Zhou enjoyed the music of the Son of Heaven.'\n\nAnother asked about the creative function of ghosts and spirits, which I had explained. 'When people are born, none lack the true essence of the limitless and the vital essence of the two and five, all within the function of creation. Where do they return when they die?'\n\n'The body and soul return to earth; the vital qi goes everywhere.'\n\n'When it goes, does it have form?'\n\n'Ghosts have no form.'\n\n'Do they have sound?'\n\n'Ghosts have no sound.'\n\n'Do they have mind?'\n\n'Ghosts have no mind.'\n\n'With no form, no sound, no mind, how do you say that if one exhausts sincerity they receive? What receives?'\n\n'Qi receives.'\n\n'How do you know qi receives?'\n\n'I know it by examining my own mind. Qi gathers to form humans; qi disperses to form ghosts. The principle between others and myself is one. How much more between ancestors and descendants? Their breathing and pulse are connected to the body—there is no boundary between here and there. When descendants sense this, the divine spirit is moved. Its radiance is clear and beyond doubt.'\n\n'Therefore when one is solemn and pure, and reverent as if meeting parents again, with this sincerity clear in the heart's chamber, what is said to have no form can manifest form; what is said to have no sound can manifest sound; what is said to have no mind can manifest mind. It shines on left and right, fills above and below, bursts forth like plants in bloom. The Poetry says \"support my thought and complete it.\" The Book of Changes says \"to know the condition of ghosts and spirits is this.\"\n\nOne asked, 'Do the sage and ordinary person have the same ghosts?'\n\n'Both same and different. Sage and commoner both obtain heaven and earth's principle and the five elements' qi to live. But the sage follows inborn nature while the commoner follows external things, hence the difference. When they die, the spirit-qi scatters and dissipates. Only principle remains. Can principle be two? In this they are the same. If one follows principle unto death, all from ordinary persons to superior intelligence are thus. Yet occasionally the wicked or poor who act against principle and die may become vengeful ghosts. Therefore the Book praises sages: \"The Shang exalted ritual, matching heaven.\" The Poetry praises sages: \"King Wen ascends and descends on heaven's left and right.\" How could the wicked or poor compare? In this they differ.'\n\nOne asked, 'Then does worshipping spirits bring blessings? Is this also principle?'\n\n'Yes.'\n\n'But you say ghosts have no form, sound, or mind. Then what brings misfortune or fortune?'\n\n'The receiving or not receiving of the spirit's offerings, and a person's misfortune or fortune, are silently determined in darkness by themselves. It is not that spirits curse one and bless another. Like a farmer working his field: plant little, harvest little; plant much, harvest much. This is humans bringing misfortune and fortune upon themselves, not spirits cursing them with it.'\n\n'Now the shamans say: \"Spirits each have form and mind. When they afflict people with illness, if one sets out wine and food and prays, the spirit gets drunk and satisfied, becomes pleased, and removes the illness.\" This departs far from principle.'\n\nOne asked, 'What grounds does Zhu Xi have for saying \"prayer is correct principle\"?'\n\nI said, 'Spirits have no selfishness. The official serves the lord, the child the father, the wife the husband, the younger the elder, the friend the friend. When this urgent sincerity lacks even a hair's breadth of falsity and is pure in heaven's principle, there is responding and being moved without being sought. Beyond this point, words cannot describe it. The Duke of Zhou's prayer in the metal vessel, Jianlu's prayer to the North Star, the breaking of ice revealing fish as with Wang Xiang, bamboo shoots sprouting in winter as with Meng Zong—could these happen without principle?'\n\nOne asked, 'Why then did not spirits aid the sage Confucius? Why did ghosts not bless the loyal Bi Gan?'\n\nI answered, 'This is what we call transformation. Yet Bi Gan's tomb soil had barely dried when his posthumous rank was granted. Confucius receives ten thousand generations of royal sacrifice, honored above Yao and Shun, his descendants enjoying the pleasures of nobles, continuing two thousand years hence. Have spirits truly not aided him?'\n\nOne asked, 'If shamans depart from principle as you say, should we disbelieve all their practices?'\n\nI replied, 'Spirit and human are one body. If shamans were sincere without falsity like Wu Xian, would they not commune with spirits? The Rites say the shaman master led male and female shamans. When the nation suffered great drought, they performed the rain dance. When great calamity came, they performed the eternal shaman ritual. When the lord mourned a minister, shamans went first with peach branches. The Left Commentary records how the Jin shaman knew Duke Jing would not eat new grain. The Book of Han tells how the woman Bi reported to Wang Mang the anger of the High Temple. The Analects say \"a person without constancy cannot become a shaman-physician.\" From this we see the art is not one fools can master.'\n\n'Yet today's shamans typically practice left-path arts, making fools of the common people. The sun and moon and stars—only the Son of Heaven sacrifices. Shamans set up Seven Star spirits. Famous mountains and great rivers—only lords sacrifice. Shamans invoke mountain and river spirits. People's illnesses come from unsettled original qi, but shamans say spirits afflict them, fabricating baseless tales and wasting useless money. People's misfortune and fortune come from their own good and evil deeds, but shamans say worshipping spirits brings fortune and neglecting them brings misfortune. Foolish people honor, believe, clothe and feed them, poisoning the state and harming the people like nothing else. Is this not departing from principle? This is what I meant.'\n\nOne asked, 'If shamans cannot be trusted, do those who divine attribute spirits like Fuxi, King Wen, the Duke of Zhou, Confucius, Yuan Tiankang, Li Chunfeng, Chen Xifeng and Shao Kangzi as spirits? Can we trust this?'\n\nI said, 'We can.'\n\n'Why must one seek from the Four Sages and Four Worthies rather than other spirits?'\n\n'The Four Sages and Four Worthies are not uniquely different from other spirits. We honor and elevate them because they established the system.'\n\n'Is there principle in seeking divination from ghosts and spirits?'\n\n'There is. Ghosts and spirits are the Way. If one seeks according to their principle, the spirit will surely tell through divination. If what one seeks is not according to principle and one's inquiry lacks sincerity, the spirit may refuse and not answer. Therefore the responsibility of official divination has always been held important. Today's diviners seek what is not according to principle; those who divine interpret carelessly. The spirit does not descend to tell; the divination does not match the hexagrams. People think divination is not a sage's method, but this is mistaken.'\n\nOne asked, 'Should we then seek divination for everything?'\n\nI said, 'In this degenerate age when the Way weakens, there are no skilled diviners. Thus divination becomes mere deception. How can we trust people's divinations for setting policy?'\n\nOne asked, 'If divination cannot be trusted, what of geomancy? Do those who practice it truly use stars like Four Prosperity, Four Greed, Four Culture, Three Martial, Aide, Great, Assistant, Four Cleanliness and Two Breaking to mark the eight directions, determining fortune and misfortune by water's flow and breaking? Do they see the green dragon and white tiger of mountains, determining prosperity and calamity by their orientation? Is there truth to this?'\n\nI said, 'It is vague and unclear. Yet I privately suspect: when a certain mountain blocks a certain corner, wind-qi becomes harmonious; when certain water flows a certain way, water-qi becomes disturbed. To judge the safety of the living by wind-water's harmony and disturbance approaches principle. But to say \"a certain spirit guards a certain direction, a certain star reaches a certain place, water offending a certain spirit brings misfortune, water entering a certain star brings fortune, the green dragon fleeing brings misfortune, the white tiger coming brings fortune\"—this greatly deceives people. Even gentlemen are ashamed to speak of such things.'\n\nOne said, 'I have heard your explanations of sacrifice, blessing and misfortune, shamans and spirits communing, and geomancy approaching principle. Now the Buddhist teaching says: when people die their consciousness does not die, persisting through countless eons without perishing, receiving human form again. Do you say they are all wrong, having no form and no mind?'\n\nI answered, 'The Limitless and Great Ultimate are principle. Yin, yang and the five elements are qi. When people live, principle and qi unite, residing in physical form—this is mind. When people die and the body decays, principle remains principle, qi remains qi. When language has not finished, the material form becomes earth. Where then would mind or form exist? The Buddha's deceptive doctrine breaks of itself without attack.'\n\n'Then how can cold become warm and warm become cold, day become night and night become day, with something going and coming again, something coming and going again, unless people could become human again?'\n\n'The qi of heaven and earth has beginning and end, arrival and return, birth and death, but certainly not the principle that the ended restarts, the departed returns, or the dead revive. When the year ends in past winter, spring's life comes from next year's qi. When the night ends in past evening, morning's time comes from tomorrow's qi. When tree leaves fall, spring comes for leaves to grow again. When breathing ends, original qi moves for breath to arise again. This is certainly not departed things returning or dead things reviving. The hells' karma and the six realms' retribution arise from this. Scholars should clearly refute this, or the principle of ghosts and spirits cannot finally be illuminated.'\n\n'But then why did Liang Xiao dying afflict Zheng? Why did Peng Sheng dying afflict Duke Xiang of Qi? Why did Ru Yi dying afflict Mother Lü? Why did Guan Fu dying afflict Tian Fen? If ghosts have no mind, are these not deceptions?'\n\nI said, 'These are not deceptions, but one principle within the Way. When a person obtains this principle and is born, following this principle to the end, the hun ascends and the po descends—that is all. How could a mere mind lurk in the chest bestowing power and fortune? But if the principle obtained was incomplete and one suddenly dies by the sword, the mind condenses without dispersing, resentment coalesces without releasing, and the sinister, foul qi may indeed have principle to strike and kill people. This is the transformation of ghosts and spirits, not the normal principle.'\n\n'Are not the weeping of ghosts in ancient battlefields when skies darken and the sometimes-appearing fire at night deceptions?'\n\n'Not deceptions, but transformations of principle. They too did not meet proper endings. Their qi coalesced without resolving, unable to merge with qi's general flow. Meeting rain and night, yin meets yin, steaming forth creates form, rising creates sound. Is this without principle?'\n\n'Like how in mountain forests when wind blows, the leaves of great trees a hundred spans around, struck and shaken, create sounds like nose, mouth, ear, beam, cup, mortar, depression, filth—swishing, rustling, scolding, breathing, shouting, whistling, rising, gnawing—the front utters while behind responds. Thunder and lightning burst from empty space, shaking hundreds of miles around, splitting wood and stone, ringing metal and iron. Who causes this? Ghosts and spirits. People, familiar with wind and thunder yet rarely seeing ghostly strangeness, do not find it strange in wind and thunder but strange in ghostly strangeness. Yet ultimately these are not strange. Zhang Nanxuan once saw such strangeness—he was no mere babbler.'\n\n'Then do such vengeful spirits persist eternally with heaven and earth, never perishing?'\n\n'No. With time they naturally perish. Like fire barely extinguished: there remains warmth steaming forth, making hands hot if touched, but with time that qi vanishes completely.'\n\n'Yet Zilu dying by the sword did not become a phantom. Qu Yuan dying by misfortune did not become a vengeful ghost. What principle is this?'\n\n'The sage knows fortune and misfortune are one stream. The understanding person knows death and life are one principle. Therefore when Confucius was surrounded he still played the stringed instrument. When Zeng Xi attended the dead he sang. He never made death and life causes for worry or joy. Therefore the commoner calls it death, the gentleman calls it completion. Both Zilu and Qu Yuan followed principle in their completion, merging with one qi. Observe: Zilu said \"though the gentleman dies, he does not remove his cap.\" Qu Yuan said \"grasping fragrant herb to shield my tears, wetting my robe's hem with waves. Boundlessly vast, unable to measure, streaking endless, unable to untangle. Regretting what I hoped for in former days, grieving the distant future.\" Yet their graceful ease and unshaken bearing reveal their condition. Where is resentment like Liang Xiao? Zhuangzi said \"when the Master came it was timely; when he left it was in order.\" This applies to both.'\n\n'Yet Qu Yuan said \"embracing sweet orchids to shield tears,\" showing sorrow. How could he not become a vengeful ghost?'\n\n'But did not Qu Yuan say \"lest my body dread affliction, fearing the royal chariot's defeat\"? Then Qu Yuan's sorrow was sorrow for his nation. Qu Yuan's joy was making death and life as one. Ancients were simple: whether speaking good or evil, it came from their nature. Such words were never for personal benefit. Where then is principle for becoming vengeful?'\n\n'Then what of Li Fei, reclining in her chamber, appearing to the Han emperor at Weiyang Palace? Or Chen Shuobao, not dying by blade, rebuking the Sui emperor at Leitang? What principle is this?'\n\nI said, 'Such a person is unvirtuous, righteousness completely lost, their nature biased and devious, desire damming the heart, hatred coalescing within without venting—they become no different from those dying violently. Thus such strangeness appears in them. Yet the ordinary person upward has no such strangeness. When Li Fei was dying, the emperor came to see her personally. She covered herself with a quilt and refused, saying \"my appearance has become dreadful and I cannot receive you thus.\" The emperor insisted but could not see her, left displeased. Her sisters reproached her. She said, \"not seeing the emperor is precisely to entrust our siblings for the long term. She who uses beauty to serve loses love when beauty fades. The emperor yearns for me only for my appearance. Now seeing my face changed, he will surely be disgusted and discard me. How then could he cherish our siblings?\" \n\nSee how she was calculating and cunning in life. Surely lay resentment for eternal separation from spouse and grief for dying in bloom in her breast.\n\nChen Shuobao in life pitifully cherished fleeting years, indulging without limit, counting one day as ten in its preciousness. His \"Rear Courtyard Flower\" reveals this. In the end, the sorrow of the empty well and the grief of lost kingdom—could these be forgotten in his heart? So that both died with ghostly strangeness perhaps has reason. Yet sorcerers have many transformative techniques, able to make dying persons' eyes see illusions. How do you know Li Fei's appearance was not from Shao Weng's technique? How do you guarantee Chen Shuobao's appearance did not arise from Yang Guang's loss of mind?'\n\n'Then why do some meeting vengeful ghosts not die, or seeing strangeness not sicken?'\n\n'Because one maintains singular focus without wavering, divine clarity moves, so weeping can make images plow, stringed music can make enemies retreat. Much less can sinister, foul qi intrude. During the Xianning period, great plague could not infect Yu Gong—how much less those worthier than Yu Gong?'\n\nOne asked, 'I have heard your explanations of Buddhism's seeming rightness yet wrongness, and humanity and ghosts existing and not existing. Yet some call out in empty silence, speaking though pursuit reveals nothing; some rely on humans and speak through language, predicting human fortune and misfortune sometimes accurately, sometimes not. Some based on water curse people calling them dragons and phantoms; some based on mountains curse people calling them mountain phantoms. Are these also ghosts or deceptions?'\n\n'Neither ghost nor deception. Ghosts are yin essence, their substance quiet and silent—how could they speak with people? Purely strong and upright, sharing virtue with heaven and earth—how could they curse? Moreover heaven covers and earth sustains billions among billions, each visible to ten eyes, pointed to by ten hands. How could deception occur? This is simply the turbid qi between heaven and earth. It is what Han Yu called physical strangeness.'\n\n'One qi flows, moving robustly to become heaven, resting solidly to become earth, bright to become sun and moon, moist to become rain and dew, coagulated to become frost and snow, circling without ceasing to become wind and thunder, subtly united with principle to become humans and creatures, extending and contracting, moving and returning to become ghosts and spirits. Why does such turbid qi emerge?'\n\n'Physical things, when old, move; when moving, change—this is principle. Like how the Yellow River, springing from Kunlun, initially flows as one stream with no variation. Yet gradually the lower course expands, rushing to become the Intercrossing River, collecting to become Salt Marsh, piercing through Accumulated Stone, severing Grindstone, crossing Dragon Gate, passing over Thunder Peak, flowing into the Eastern Sea. Struck it becomes thunder-lightning; shaken it becomes wind-rain; its wave-sound shakes heaven and earth—its momentum makes it so.\n\nHeaven and earth have existed long; their qi usage is much. When qi usage is much, turbid qi schemes among it—this too is principle. Like how an object casts a shadow, an egg can bear young.'\n\nOne said, 'If what you say is true, the virtue of ghosts and spirits is indeed great. Yet I once heard the former Sicheng Zhang Jiyi say \"when people first die, ghosts and spirits exist; after long time, no ghosts.\" Your explanation of ghosts does not distinguish long or short, directly pointing to \"radiant on left and right, filling above and below, blooming like plants.\" And Guangling Li Kuanyi said \"there are no ghosts between heaven and earth; what we call heaven, earth, and human spirits are merely borrowed words. As for mountain demons, wood demons, vengeful ghosts, and phantoms—these are all fabrications, untrustworthy, departing far from principle, impossible things.\" Yet your explanation of ghosts differs: your discussion of ancestor-worship is very clear; your discussion of physical strangeness and vengeful ghosts says all are qi's transformations, not deceptions. These two masters' explanations were the finest of their time, and you too once studied under them. Why do your views differ?'\n\nI said, 'Qi's proper function is ghosts and spirits. Whether becoming human or ghost, qi has no distinction between here and there. What we call proper function—can it have a principle of starting then ceasing? If these masters are right, the Yellow Emperor and Zhurong, their era remote, would have no spirits to receive sacrifice; Confucius and Yan Hui, dead a thousand years, would benefit from no offerings. Yet why have enlightened rulers and worthy ministers since the Three Dynasties, creating ritual and music, never deemed the sacrifice to ancient sages improper? The Book says \"the temples of seven generations observe virtue.\" Thus Shang's Zhonzong and Gaozong, Zhou's Wen Temple and Wu Temple, remained unchanged throughout their dynasties' reigns. If Shang and Zhou had maintained ancestral sacrifice for billions of years without ceasing, then Gaozong, Zhonzong, Wen Temple and Wu Temple would continue unchanged for billions of years. Where is the principle of long time bringing no spirits?\n\nZhang's explanation seems apt for vengeful ghosts but greatly contradicts the principle of ghosts and spirits—his error is not small. Li's \"no ghosts\" explanation is somewhat more reasonable. Yet while his saying \"ghosts and spirits have no sound or smell\" may hold, his saying \"there are no ghosts between heaven and earth\" may violate principle.\n\nAll physical things have two ends: one shadowed, one bright; one arriving, one departing—this is it. Hearing one reveals two; seeing this reveals that. Yet worldly scholars know only what the eye sees, not investigating the unexpected, thus \"no ghosts\" appears. As for qi's transformation becoming demons, vengeful ghosts and strangeness, yet principle encompasses all things without omission—this too is possibly so. Speaking transformation without normality becomes skewed and incorrect; speaking normality without transformation becomes rigid and unflowing. I dare not follow Li's explanation.'\n\nOne said, 'I have heard Zhang's errors. Someone asked Li: \"You say no ghosts, yet the Poetry and Books speak clearly of the ghostly Way. Why?\" Li answered: \"Once a fellow from my village asked me: do humans have blood-connection to their mother? I said: have you seen the five grains? Planted in earth and growing, yet no branch, root, or leaf connects to earth. The planter is like the father, the earth like the mother. The mother's work equals the father's, yet no blood connection exists. This fellow returned and complained to his mother: by Li's words, mother has no kindness to me—from this filial piety declined. Surely the child could not grasp the meaning. Yet from this, the Five Sacrifices and Eight Sacrifices mentioned in the classics, the Suburban Sacrifice and home ritual texts—all merely teach people to return to their roots, not that ghosts truly exist, this is clear.\" Is this all wrong?'\n\n'His view is high, yet actually contradicts the Seal of Unity where bone connects to father and flesh to mother. That he told such a story is like telling dreams to a sleeper—he cannot escape responsibility. And to say the classics use borrowed language is even more skewed. The sage teaches by the straight Way, as clear as hung sun and moon. This differs from the Buddha's deception to move people toward good. If ghosts truly did not exist yet the sage taught people to return to their roots, this would be deception itself. Do you think the sage deceives?'\n\nOne asked, 'Human ghosts when dead surely exist. But you say demons and vengeful ghosts truly exist, not deceptions. Now in plague-struck houses sickness transmits among people. Do people truly call this ghosts?'\n\n'This is not ghosts but heaven-moving qi.'\n\n'Heaven's task is birth and growth. How could it carry poison-qi?'\n\n'Human action causes infection. When human qi harmonizes below, heavenly qi harmonizes above. When human qi twists below, heaven's Way responds above. Perhaps after great drought and famine, or during military campaigns and construction, the moans and cries of pain wound the life-qi—not that the Director of Fate intends to harm things.'\n\n'Now when plague strikes, people forbid wine, sound and desire. Those who transgress see the plague worsen. Is this true?'\n\n'Yes. Wine unsettles the heart, sound disturbs the heart, desire deludes the heart. When the heart lacks unity, sickness transmits.'\n\n'Certain regions have many cough diseases, certain regions many beriberi. In our country, Pyongyang and Hwanghae have much cough, Chungcheong and Jeolla have much beriberi. Do people truly call this ghosts?'\n\n'This is not ghosts but earth-yielded sickness.'\n\n'Earth's task is growth. Why would it emit poison?'\n\n'Wind-qi is mindless. Meeting unusual water and soil it naturally becomes miasmic poison. If people's hearts do not guard their bodies, contact brings natural sickness, violation brings possible death. Yet earth has no mind to harm people.'\n\n'When people see malaria they say the Flame Emperor's son causes it. Is this a ghost?'\n\n'This is not a ghost. Cold and heat disharmony, the five organs wounded—this brings the sickness.'\n\n'Yet the sickness has regular intervals. When sorcerers threaten it retreats; when one avoids it one escapes. Since High Force and Du Fu, all have been thus. Is it not still a ghost?'\n\n'The sincerity of ghosts and spirits lies in heaven and earth, boundless and full like water in the earth. If ghosts truly cursed through sickness, where could one flee where threatening brings no fear? Like when people sin and beg forgiveness with trembling words, telling their misfortune—sometimes people forgive. But if one resists and plunders, who does not anger? If humans are thus, how much more spirits. This principle cannot possibly exist.'\n\n'Then why do people using methods sometimes escape?'\n\n'The heart is the body's master. When the heart harmonizes without twisting, there is no sickness from the start. Yet people, blocked by external troubles, lose heart focus, gaining the sickness. When deeply believing a sorcerer's arts, the heart eases and qi flows smoothly, so sickness naturally retreats. This too is a principle's manifestation.'\n\n'When pustule-rash strikes, the ear hears strange sounds, the eyes see strange things, mad words and rambling speech startle those nearby. Are these ghosts?'\n\n'These are not ghosts but wind-cold attacking externally, empty-heat and poison-pulse caused. From suspicion and fear, one perhaps sees physical strangeness or dreams of seeing ghosts—not truly having ghostly affliction.'\n\n'Pustule-rash disease has five types. One encountered brings lifelong immunity. People say the pustule-rash ghost is clever and desires nothing, hence this. Is this true?'\n\n'This is not ghosts. Humans at birth necessarily drink evil broth. When seasonal qi strikes externally and evil poison responds internally, sickness follows. Its storage in the five organs makes its manifestation also fivefold. Drinking the broth not twice means the sickness comes not twice. How could a ghost cause this? Yet physicians have detailed cures for sickness. When today's people call it a ghost's sickness without using medicines, they risk destruction. This is worse than unfilial impiety.'\n\n'Almanac makers list four-directional ghosts. When moving earth something stirs—is this true?'\n\n'This cannot be trusted. The earth spirit bears responsibility for bearing all things, hence does not anger at earth-moving. Calling it earth-spirit suffices. How could it have names like Great General Scholar? Earth is not angered at moving. Heaven moves robustly thus moving; earth moves submissively thus moving. Earth's symbol is the mare's constancy, taking its moving quality. Thus spring plowing, summer hoeing, the five elements mutually overcome to bear five grains. When the grains mature, earth is sacrificed—earth spirit hardly angers at earth-moving. If one does not hoe and dig earth, plows do not work it, the five grains cannot grow and earth sacrifice cannot occur. Then what benefit in earth not moving for the earth spirit? Today's people deeply believe false arts to the point of houses tilting and walls crumbling, yet fear to repair them, often bringing collapse-disasters. What a pity.'\n\n'In houses of the dead, specialists point out \"this day person\" and \"this time person\" as targets of avoidance—the father dying so the son flees the mourning, the husband dying so the wife stops weeping. The specialist takes the household's food and clothing to sacrifice to the ghost, saying \"only thus escape death.\" Is this true?'\n\n'This cannot be trusted. That ghosts do not curse people I explained before in detail. That human death and life are determined by heaven rewarding goodness and punishing evil—no scheme escapes it, no technique avoids it. This is merely baseless schemes to seize food and clothing while greatly corrupting customs.\n\nAlas! Since the Way became unclear, shamans, Buddhists, and sorcerers have clouded people's ears and drowned the world in filth. Though visiting each household explaining ghost and spirit distinctions, the matter cannot succeed.'\n\nOne asked, 'Your explanation is fitting, sufficient to clear the world's confusion. Yet nowadays when people encounter such afflictions, some truly see ghostly manifestations with visible forms. You alone insist these are not ghosts but result from extreme suspicion and fear, sometimes seeing strange things. Could you elaborate on the details?'\n\nI said, 'Lately the calendar master Kim Siseup told me: once a Zen monk at night went to the latrine. Descending the steps he stepped on and killed a creature—there was a crunching sound. The monk thought: at midday a golden toad lay under the steps; the creature surely stepped-killed must be the toad. He grew frantic, unable to sleep, convinced he would enter hell suffering the reward for toad-killing.\n\nToward dawn he fitfully dozed, dreaming the toad sued him in the afterlife's court. An ox-headed demon came binding him before the Ten Kings, about to apply torture, sending him to the Avici hell. The monk awoke, more convinced. Sitting and awaiting dawn, he rose and looked under the steps. The toad was not there—only melon seeds lay shattered where his foot had pressed. Thus was the case.\n\nAnother: a scholar wandered a mountain at dark night hearing weeping sounds. Following them they grew closer and louder. At a cave he listened carefully—the sound came from between stones. Advancing to look, he seemed to see leaves blocking the stream making sound. Removing leaves the sound stopped; replacing them the sound resumed. Settling his spirit and listening carefully, he heard only water sounds, not weeping. Retreating to where he first heard weeping, the sound resumed as before.\n\nThese two cases: the first—not truly hellish demons weeping; the second—not truly hearing weeping ghosts. Yet suspicion and fear created manifestation in the mind. The heart, when grasped, exists; when released, perishes. When it perishes, deviant thoughts arise. When deviant thoughts arise, things merely draw it along. When things draw it along without knowing how to preserve it, essence-spirit wastes, fatigue spreads, the hundred pulses cloud and unclear, the formless appears formed before the eyes, the soundless appears sounding in the ears. Gradually worsening to the point of no rescue, the heart-spirit follows dissipating, the form-qi follows scattering. All who see such people think truly that ghosts and strangeness curse them. Is this principle?\n\nFrom this observe: people without personal wisdom, lacking teacher-friend resources, ignorant of nature-principle study, terrified by fortune-misfortune tales—should they enter nighttime as entering an unpopulated realm, none escape such afflictions. Dongfeng's this explanation is the finest compass for shattering delusion. Thus I cite it as evidence.\n\nYet this is merely the outline. The primal qi scattered spreads through all things' surfaces—ghosts and spirits are one root's myriad forms. Gathering and reducing them to the ultimate unified principle—ghosts and spirits are myriad forms' one root. Then what is called heaven-moving and earth-moving qi, pustule-rash sickness's five types from sensation-trauma, malaria and pustule-rash sickness from charlatans' deception, earth spirit and target-calling's deceit—nothing escapes principle-qi. Though calling them ghosts and spirits is acceptable, yet speaking to this point suits those who investigate the natures of things, not casual speech to common folk.'\n\nOne rose twice bowing: \"Understood.\"\n\nThereupon I composed this discourse."
  footnotes:
    - 'The opening dialogue presents the fundamental problem: ghosts and spirits seem paradoxically both present and absent, visible yet elusive. This paradox structures Nam Hyooun''s entire investigation.'
    - 'The etymology provided—gui (鬼) as ''return'' and shen (神) as ''extend''—provides a key interpretive framework: all dispersing and returning are ghosts; all gathering and extending are spirits. This suggests a monistic metaphysics where qi undergoes cyclical transformations.'
    - 'Nam invokes classical authorities carefully: Confucius avoided speaking of spirits and the supernatural; even Zhu Xi merely ''barely mentioned'' such matters. Nam''s modesty about his own inadequacy follows traditional scholarly protocol.'
    - The five sacrifices (五祀) and eight sacrifices (八蜡) represent different categories of ritual spirits—household, agricultural, and natural forces. Their inclusion suggests a hierarchical but interconnected spiritual ecosystem.
    - 'Nam''s critique of contemporary shamanism is sharp: shamans wrongly claim spirits have individual forms, minds, and vengeful intentions, misleading people into wasteful practices. By contrast, authentic ritual depends on human sincerity creating resonance with principle itself.'
    - 'The discussion of qi receiving offerings without form or consciousness parallels Neo-Confucian metaphysics: the universe responds to sincere intention through principle (li) rather than through any anthropomorphic mechanism.'
    - Nam's engagement with Buddhism's theory of rebirth directly challenges its foundational claim that consciousness persists after death. His counterargument relies on the complete dispersal of qi after death, leaving only abstract principle.
    - 'The historical examples of vengeful spirits (Liang Xiao, Peng Sheng, etc.) are not denied but reinterpreted: they represent residual qi patterns of those who died with unresolved resentment, not conscious entities bent on revenge. This explains spirit manifestations while maintaining that spirits lack agency or malice.'
    - The extended discussion of epidemic diseases, regional illnesses, and malaria displaces supernatural causation with environmental and physiological explanations. Medical principle replaces demonic possession.
    - Kim Siseup's anecdotes about the monk and the scholar demonstrate how suspicion and fear generate phantom experiences through the mind's power to shape perception. This psychological explanation represents the high point of Nam's rationalist critique.
    - Nam's final synthesis acknowledges both the constancy of principle (spirits' permanent dimension) and the changeability of qi (spirits' transformative dimension). This allows room for acknowledged mystery while excluding superstitious misinterpretation.
